<TITLE> Kolkata businesses offer to invest big </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 6 (bdnews24.com)Businesses from India's West Bengal capital of Calcutta have offered to make huge investment in Bangladesh, an aide to the prime minister has said. A delegation from the Indian Chamber of Commerce, Calcutta expressed the interest at a meeting with prime minister Sheikh Hasina Monday, said her press secretary Abul Kalam Azad told reporters. The five-member ICC delegation headed by president Sanjay Budhia saw with the prime minister at 10:30am. Hasina urged the Indian businessmen to invest in the under-process specialised economic zone, Azad said. The meeting, also attended by commerce minister Faruq Khan, the prime minister's economic and commerce adviser Mashiur Rahman and the Awami League chief's investment adviser Salman F Rahman, discussed other business issues and trade balancing. Azad said Hasina told the delegates she would like to see both public and the private sector development. "The delegates told the prime minister that thanks to her wisdom and sagacity, she has established herself not only as Bangladesh's leader but also as the regional leader by now," said Azad. Hasina assured them that the government would think about their proposal that a Bangladesh deputy high commission or a consulate office was set up at Guawahati, the capital of northeastern Assam state. At around 11:30am, Indian high commissioner Pinak Ranjan Chakravarti, who has been away in India for over a month undergoing treatment, called on the prime minister. The envoy condoled the February killings of army officers deputed to border forcer BDR at Peelkhana. They discussed maritime boundaries and other bilateral issues. bd
